'''Minezuka Kofun''' (峯塚古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Tenri City|ja|天理市|12=draft}}, Nara Prefecture, Japan. The Kofun, shaped as a circular mound, is part of the {{ill|Somanochi Kofun Group|ja|杣之内古墳群|1=Somanouchi Kofun cluster|12=draft}} and is not designation1 as a historic site.

== Overview ==

The kofun is a large circular Kofun built at the southern foot of a small hill ridge extending east from the eastern edge of the {{ill|Nara Basin|ja|奈良盆地|12=draft}}.<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard">Explanatory board at the site.</ref> A survey was conducted by the {{ill|Tenri University History Research Society|ja|天理大学歴史研究会|12=draft}} in 1969,<ref name="HinoHiroshi"/> but no excavation has been carried out to date.

The mound is circular, built in three tiers. The first tier measures 35.5 meters in diameter, the second tier 28.4 meters, and the third tier 17.6 meters. The mound stands approximately 5 meters tall.<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/> The outer surface of the mound features rectangular blocks of tuff sandstone (Tenri sandstone), giving it a brick-like appearance.<ref name="HinoHiroshi"/><ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/> There is also speculation about the presence of a surrounding moat.<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/> The burial facility consists of a double-sleeve horizontal stone chamber that opens to the south.<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/> This meticulously constructed large chamber uses cut stones of granite, resembling the chamber of {{ill|Iwayayama Kofun|ja|岩屋山古墳|12=draft}} in {{ill|Asuka Village|ja|明日香村|12=draft}} and is classified as an Iwayayama-type chamber. However, the burial goods remain unclear due to early looting.<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/>

The kofun is estimated to date back to the early to mid-7th century during the {{ill|Late Kofun Period|ja|終末期古墳|1=Late Kofun tumuli|12=draft}}.<ref name="HinoHiroshi"/> It is considered one of the most representative late kofun in Nara Prefecture and was constructed with a stone chamber comparable to those in imperial Kofuns.<ref name="HinoHiroshi"/> Nearby kofun include the large {{ill|Tsukaana-yama Kofun|ja|塚穴山古墳|12=draft}}, a predecessor of Minezuka Kofun. Additionally, the sophisticated {{ill|Somanochi Cremation Tomb|ja|杣之内火葬墓|12=draft}}, featuring a {{ill|Sea-beast grape mirror|ja|海獣葡萄鏡|12=draft}}, suggests these mounds may have belonged to the leaders of the {{ill|Mononobe clan|ja|物部氏|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Shiraishi Taichirō|title=Understanding Kofun Period Burials (Chūōkōron Series)|year=2018|pages=253–260}}</ref><ref name="HinoHiroshi"/> The similarities in construction material and technique with the {{ill|Sakafuneishi Site|ja|酒船石遺跡|12=draft}} further indicate the influence of the reign of {{ill|Empress Saimei|ja|斉明天皇|12=draft}}.<ref name="HinoHiroshi"/>

== burial ==
[[File:Minezuka Kofun, 3D-P.jpg|thumb|300px|right|{{center|Perspective drawing of the stone chamber}}]]
[[File:Minezuka Kofun, 3D-N.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Layout drawing of the stone chamber}}]]
The burial facility consists of a double-sleeve horizontal stone chamber that opens to the south. The area of the chamber are as follows:<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/><ref>{{Harvid|杣之内古墳群の研究|2014}}</ref>:
* Total Length: 11.11 meters
* Burial Chamber: Length 4.46 meters, Width 2.58 meters (rear wall) / 2.60 meters (entrance), Height 2.4 meters
* Passage: Length 6.65 meters, Width 2.28 meters, Height 1.70 meters

The chamber, constructed with granite cut stones, features blocks as large as 4.5 meters in width and 1.2 meters in height.<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/> Both the rear and side walls of the chamber are built in two tiers, with plaster used to seal the joints.<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/> The ceiling of the chamber consists of three stones.<ref name="ExplanatoryBoard"/>

The chamber shares characteristics with the {{ill|Iwayayama Kofun|ja|岩屋山古墳|12=draft}}, leading to its classification as an "Iwayayama-style stone chamber." The chamber area align closely with the {{ill|Kotani Kofun|ja|小谷古墳|12=draft}}, indicating shared construction designs. This suggests a shift in stonemason management from regional clans to the imperial court during the Late Kofun Period.<ref name="Kawakami">{{Cite book|author=Kawakami Kunihiko|title=Discovering Asuka|year=2004|pages=66–69}}</ref>
